How to Finance the Green Transition
New York — This week, world leaders gathered in New York at the United Nations to assess the global battle against climate change and submit new commitments to reduce emissions.
The climate crisis is of great importance, and our pace of action is far too slow.
We were unable to shift into high gear for a long time.
Accelerating the pace of change requires collaborative efforts from both public and private sectors.
Fortunately, through the work of the Climate Finance Leadership Initiative (CFLI), private sector collaboration to combat climate change is increasingly growing.
The Climate Finance Leadership Initiative (CFLI) was established under the leadership of Michael Bloomberg, the UN Special Envoy for Climate Action, with the aim of mobilizing private capital at the global level to address this critical issue.
This month, CFLI released a new report titled "Financing the Low Carbon Future," which outlines how to expand green finance to support an orderly transition to a low-carbon economy and highlights public-private partnership opportunities to achieve the targets of the 2015 Paris Climate Agreement.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) is the largest multilateral investor in climate-related projects worldwide.
But today, in response to the call from the heads of state of European countries and the newly elected President of the European Commission, Ursula von der Leyen, we are ready to demonstrate greater ambition and strengthen the role of the EIB as the EU's specialized climate bank.
The EIB will mainstream climate considerations, target low-carbon investments, and commit at least 100 billion euros to low-carbon projects over the next decade.
To achieve this goal, at least 50% of EIB financing will be allocated to climate action and environmental sustainability by 2025.
By the end of 2020, we will align all our financing activities with the goals of the Paris Climate Agreement.
As an important first step, we will exclude energy projects that rely on fossil fuels.
In addition, we will position the EIB as a green finance incubator, committed to mobilizing other resources to assist economies in their transition toward a low-carbon future.
As a European Union bank, our mission is to invest in Europe's future, with climate change being the most important issue among them.
The more urgent the climate crisis, the stronger our determination.
It was this summer that European countries experienced record-breaking high temperatures and poor crop yields, caused by last year's drought.
Many developing countries have had similar experiences.
Floods and other climate-related phenomena cost major cities billions of dollars each year and threaten even more lives.
But the climate crisis is also an opportunity, as funding new green infrastructure can create jobs, stimulate economic growth, and reduce air pollution that plagues cities around the world.
Changing the investment model can accelerate the transition away from fossil fuels. This transition has already begun.
Market forces are increasingly favoring clean energy and moving away from fossil fuels.
By 2011, nearly half of the coal-fired power plants in the United States had been retired, while the clean energy sector created 3.3 million jobs, compared to less than 100,000 jobs in the coal industry.
In addition, an increasing number of U.S. cities and states have pledged to achieve net-zero emissions by 2050.
They will receive support from the Beyond Carbon initiative, launched last year by the Bloomberg Philanthropies, which aims to support the full decarbonization of the U.S. economy.
As the international community, we must not only invest in clean energy but also reduce investments in dirty energy.
Currently, in terms of fossil fuel subsidies, we are essentially spending money to promote climate change and air pollution.
These public funds should be used to guide investments toward electric vehicles and other technologies that can drive changes leading to a green transition.
These investments will yield substantial returns, including reducing the enormous costs imposed on public health by air pollution.
In addition, we can also take many measures to guide the necessary funds.
First, we must improve data and disclosure standards.
For a long time, businesses and investors have been largely unaware of climate-related risks, and have not understood the rationale for reducing carbon emissions or protecting assets from the impacts of extreme weather.
This is beginning to change.
The recommendations of the Task Force on Climate-related Financial Disclosures are guiding companies to allocate capital in a more sustainable manner, while also enabling investors to reward those companies that seriously address climate change.
Secondly, we must clarify the investment risks associated with green finance.
Cities account for more than 70% of carbon dioxide emissions, yet only a few cities in the developing world have access to credit ratings.
As a result, the total investment in clean buses, energy-efficient buildings, and other emission-reduction projects was affected.
Governments and listed banks must step up their efforts to help cities attract capital for these projects, including through initiatives such as the Global Covenant of Mayors for Climate & Energy, which is supported by the EIB and co-led by the Bloomberg Philanthropies.
Third, we need to modernize the power grid.
Incentives such as refunds and tax benefits have promoted the expansion of wind and solar power, reducing costs for both businesses and consumers.
Now, we should introduce similar programs to accelerate the deployment of battery storage and other emerging technologies, thereby speeding up the resolution of intermittency issues.
Furthermore, better grid connectivity allows regions with surplus wind and solar power to supply electricity to areas experiencing shortages.
The government can play a leading role in these two areas, encouraging more private investment to flow into clean energy.
Finally, we must continue to expand the green investment market.
In 2007, the EIB issued the world's first green bond on the Luxembourg Stock Exchange, and since then, the green bond market has grown to $136 billion.
But compared to the global bond market worth $100 trillion, it is just a drop in the bucket.
Therefore, the EIB is helping the EU develop a classification system for sustainable finance standards, enabling investors to compare similar projects just as they do with standard bonds.
More and better information about the carbon footprint of investments can enable investors to make informed decisions, thereby directing more private investment toward low-carbon projects.
This is how we provide financing for the green transition.
